### Scan Entire Page for Accessibility Issues with Playwright and Axe

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright.dev/blob/main/nodejs/versioned_docs/version-stable/accessibility-testing.mdx

This example demonstrates how to perform a full-page accessibility scan using Playwright and the `@axe-core/playwright` package. It navigates to a specified URL, runs `AxeBuilder.analyze()` to detect accessibility violations across the entire page, and then asserts that no violations were found in the scan results. This approach helps identify common, automatically detectable accessibility problems.

```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';
import AxeBuilder from '@axe-core/playwright'; // 1

test.describe('homepage', () => { // 2
  test('should not have any automatically detectable accessibility issues', async ({ page }) => {
    await page.goto('https://your-site.com/'); // 3

    const accessibilityScanResults = await new AxeBuilder({ page }).analyze(); // 4

    expect(accessibilityScanResults.violations).toEqual([]); // 5
  });
});
```

```js
const { test, expect } = require('@playwright/test');
const AxeBuilder = require('@axe-core/playwright').default; // 1

test.describe('homepage', () => { // 2
  test('should not have any automatically detectable accessibility issues', async ({ page }) => {
    await page.goto('https://your-site.com/'); // 3

    const accessibilityScanResults = await new AxeBuilder({ page }).analyze(); // 4

    expect(accessibilityScanResults.violations).toEqual([]); // 5
  });
});
```

--------------------------------

### Scan Entire Page for Accessibility Violations using Playwright and Axe-core (Java)

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright.dev/blob/main/java/versioned_docs/version-stable/accessibility-testing.mdx

This snippet demonstrates how to perform a full-page accessibility scan using Playwright and the `axe-core/playwright` Java library. It initializes Playwright, navigates to a specified URL, runs `AxeBuilder.analyze()` to detect violations across the entire page, and asserts that no violations are found using JUnit 5's `assertEquals` method.

```java
import com.deque.html.axecore.playwright.*;
import com.deque.html.axecore.utilities.axeresults.*;

import org.junit.jupiter.api.*;
import com.microsoft.playwright.*;

import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.*;

public class HomepageTests {
  @Test
  void shouldNotHaveAutomaticallyDetectableAccessibilityIssues() throws Exception {
    Playwright playwright = Playwright.create();
    Browser browser = playwright.chromium().launch();
    BrowserContext context = browser.newContext();
    Page page = context.newPage();

    page.navigate("https://your-site.com/");

    AxeResults accessibilityScanResults = new AxeBuilder(page).analyze();

    assertEquals(Collections.emptyList(), accessibilityScanResults.getViolations());
  }
}
```

--------------------------------

### Attach Accessibility Scan Results to Test in Playwright

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright.dev/blob/main/nodejs/versioned_docs/version-stable/accessibility-testing.mdx

Demonstrates attaching complete AxeBuilder scan results to a Playwright test using testInfo.attach() for debugging purposes. The scan results are serialized as JSON and can be embedded or linked by test reporters to provide comprehensive accessibility test output.

```javascript
test('example with attachment', async ({ page }, testInfo) => {
  await page.goto('https://your-site.com/');

  const accessibilityScanResults = await new AxeBuilder({ page }).analyze();

  await testInfo.attach('accessibility-scan-results', {
    body: JSON.stringify(accessibilityScanResults, null, 2),
    contentType: 'application/json'
  });

  expect(accessibilityScanResults.violations).toEqual([]);
});
```

--------------------------------

### Create Playwright Fixture for Pre-configured AxeBuilder (TypeScript/JavaScript)

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright.dev/blob/main/nodejs/versioned_docs/version-stable/accessibility-testing.mdx

This snippet defines a Playwright fixture that extends the base 'test' object to provide a 'makeAxeBuilder' function. This function returns an AxeBuilder instance pre-configured with specific WCAG tags ('wcag2a', 'wcag2aa', 'wcag21a', 'wcag21aa') and an exclusion for a commonly reused element with a known issue. This ensures consistent accessibility testing setup across all tests using this extended 'test' object.

```ts
import { test as base } from '@playwright/test';
import AxeBuilder from '@axe-core/playwright';

type AxeFixture = {
  makeAxeBuilder: () => AxeBuilder;
};

// Extend base test by providing "makeAxeBuilder"
//
// This new "test" can be used in multiple test files, and each of them will get
// a consistently configured AxeBuilder instance.
export const test = base.extend<AxeFixture>({
  makeAxeBuilder: async ({ page }, use) => {
    const makeAxeBuilder = () => new AxeBuilder({ page })
        .withTags(['wcag2a', 'wcag2aa', 'wcag21a', 'wcag21aa'])
        .exclude('#commonly-reused-element-with-known-issue');

    await use(makeAxeBuilder);
  }
});
export { expect } from '@playwright/test';
```

```js
const base = require('@playwright/test');
const AxeBuilder = require('@axe-core/playwright').default;

// Extend base test by providing "makeAxeBuilder"
//
// This new "test" can be used in multiple test files, and each of them will get
// a consistently configured AxeBuilder instance.
exports.test = base.test.extend({
  makeAxeBuilder: async ({ page }, use) => {
    const makeAxeBuilder = () => new AxeBuilder({ page })
        .withTags(['wcag2a', 'wcag2aa', 'wcag21a', 'wcag21aa'])
        .exclude('#commonly-reused-element-with-known-issue');

    await use(makeAxeBuilder);
  }
});
exports.expect = base.expect;
```

--------------------------------

### Configure Axe to Scan Specific Page Part with Playwright (JavaScript)

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright.dev/blob/main/nodejs/versioned_docs/version-stable/accessibility-testing.mdx

This example demonstrates how to configure `@axe-core/playwright` to scan only a specific part of a page using `AxeBuilder.include()`. It also illustrates how to interact with dynamic UI elements, such as clicking a button to reveal a navigation menu, and then waiting for the element to be in the desired state before running the accessibility scan. This ensures that only relevant sections are analyzed, especially for interactive components.

```js
test('navigation menu should not have automatically detectable accessibility violations', async ({
  page,
}) => {
  await page.goto('https://your-site.com/');

  await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Navigation Menu' }).click();

  // It is important to waitFor() the page to be in the desired
  // state *before* running analyze(). Otherwise, axe might not
  // find all the elements your test expects it to scan.
  await page.locator('#navigation-menu-flyout').waitFor();

  const accessibilityScanResults = await new AxeBuilder({ page })
